My thoughts rly meander in these threads so apologies if my points are a bit murky.

Kinda hard to focus when you're limited by phone typing speed and get distracted constantly by work

Iunno, I've heard them described as a "3D Metroidvania" and it's helped open my eyes to the genre as a whole. It helped me understand that these games aren't the meatgrinder dick-measuring contests that some assholes claim them to be.

It's not just boss battle after boss battle with the same player mechanics, there's a diverse set of options to choose from and play how you prefer, and fuck anyone who shits on you for playing in a way that you enjoy.

Something a lot of people neglected to mention to me about soulsbornes is that there's level up systems and a variety of builds to try out. If you keep dying to a boss, you can leave, explore elsewhere and return when you're better geared for it.

Sure the act of dying and having to restart a battle isn't fun, but I would argue it's not necessarily unfun either. There's a satisfaction of learning patterns and eventually prevailing, so long as that challenge doesn't overcome your determination.

Soulsbornes give me a very similar vibe, minus the RNG. You're not going to go into most bosses and beat them on the first try. Your deaths are a learning experience to help you climb over that brick wall. It's testing how determined you are to climb that wall.

Roguelikes, rather than being an exercise in overcoming difficulty, are moreso a test of determination. Will you dust yourself off from your failure and try again with the hope that luck is on your side, or do you give up?

In a roguelike, dying isn't necessarily a marker of difficulty. Sometimes RNG just gives you the shaft, but so long as it isn't *consistently* doing so, it's not overly difficult.

Deaths are a sign of difficulty but the per-run difficulty has a large degree of variance by design

I think there's a really bad conflation of "deaths = difficulty = unfun" in the gaming sphere and a lot of shitty people use that to gatekeep the hobby.

"Oh, you wouldn't like that game, it's too hard for you!" *implies they're superior by beating it*

It's funny because Isaac, my favorite game, had a "tough-as-nails" reputation for a while (largely came from Meat Boy pedigree/a frankly busted flash version) and I probably would've stayed away from it for longer if I didn't experience the game before hearing it.

Tbh I will never forgive gamers for branding these games as "a game for hardcore players only, you better hate yourself already because this game is so hard it'll make you cry!"

That being said, the Hollow Knight is described as a "fully grown vessel", implying that, despite them and The Knight being a similar age, vessels don't mature in the Abyss.
